{'project_name': 'WANAMEI (Árbol de vida) Conservando los bosques de Amarakaeri', 'project_summary': 'The “WANAMEI” Project is located in Peru, within the province of Manu (department of Madre de Dios), and the province of Paucartambo (department of Cusco). The Executor of the Administration Contract of the Amarakaeri Communal Reserve (ECA – Amarakaeri) is the lead project proponent and will work with Conservational International Foundation (CI) and the National Association of Administration Contract Executors of Communal Reserves from Peru (ANECAP) as co-proponents. The Project area includes the Amarakaeri Communal Reserve, its 10 associated indigenous communities and the Quero Haramba conservation concession, covering nearly 599,286 ha  

The Amarakaeri landscape is under high risk of deforestation as a result of the expansion of illegal gold mining into Madre de Dios. The main agents of deforestation are migrants, who come from neighboring regions in Peru due to the profitability of the mining activity. In addition, increasing migration to the region is driving an increase in deforestation through the conversion of forests to agriculture and cattle pastures.
The Project will reduce GHG emissions by implementing participatory conservation strategies with the indigenous communities’ partners of the ECA, and will be developed based on the RIA (Amazon Indigenous REDD+) guidelines established by indigenous national organizations as safeguards for carbon projects within their territories. These strategies include the strengthening of capacities for landscape monitoring and surveillance, developing sustainable economic activities, strengthening the organizations that lead the indigenous communities and ensuring financial sustainability of the initiative. The project expects to reduce 8.2 million tCO2 over the 30 year project lifetime with an average of 276,419tCO2 per year.', 'project_state_province': 'Madre de Dios/Manu', 'project_country': 'Peru', 'project_latitude': -12.75, 'project_longitude': -70.98}
